The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Tuesday, June 08, 2004 				 Motorola targets globetrotters
 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT																								New Delhi, June 7: Motorola, the mobile handset manufacturer, today launched Indias first quad-band phone  the V600.																								The uniqueness of quad-band technology lies in its seamless roaming facility across 800, 900, 1800 and 1900 GSM (global system for mobile communications) bands, making it functional across the globe. Priced at Rs 20,495 in India, the product is targeted at international travellers.																								Percy P. Batlivala, general manager (South-West Asia), personal communication sector, Motorola, said, The Motorola V600 marks a new beginning for the Indian consumer. It promises to keep every mobile executive connected and entertained while on the move across the globe.																								Currently, mobile phones in India functions in 900 and 1800 bands and they cannot not be used when it is taken to the Latin American countries and a few of parts in the US which operate in GSM 850 and 1900 bands. The 1900 band networks are available in countries like Argentina, Mexico, Paraguay, Bermuda island and Chile.																								In India, you can roam between 900 and 1800 with the phone seamlessly switching between the two bands. Similarly, when you take the same phone in the US or the Latin American countries it will seamlessly switch from the 850 to the 1900 band.																								Motorola is also in the process of customising a multiband mobile phone for Indian customers. The multiband phone will help the subscribers of service providers using GSM like Bharti and Hutch to enter the network of operators like Reliance Infocom and Tata who offer their services on code division multiple access technology (CDMA) technology. 
